	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New pesticide regulations raise concerns for future of smallholders</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A Dominican Republic press article in April has reported comments from a COLEACP (the ACP-EU horticultural network) advisor during a visit to the country. Morag Webb warned producers of eastern vegetables that ‘if there is no solution found for the high levels of pesticides used’ in current production for export, then the Dominican Republic is ‘at risk of losing the European market’. Webb said that the production of eastern vegetables involved ‘hundreds of small producers’, so it was ‘essential to fight high levels of pesticides residues that are being detected in these crops for export and which are not allowed in the European market’. In addition it was pointed out that this could also ‘affect other agricultural products’. Proposed measures in addition to the current technical assistance programme being run by COLEACP include the establishment of ‘a traceability system to accompany produce from the plot to the point of export’.</p><p>Pesticides regulations are also reported to be affecting Kenya. According to press reports, ‘Kenya is finding it harder to sell fresh produce to its key markets in the European Union as major supermarkets implement new pesticide regulations.’ The new regulations, which came into force in April, ‘sharply reduce allowed residue limits in pesticides’.</p><p>The situation is compounded by supermarkets adopting a zero tolerance to residue levels from dimethioate, despite an official EU permitted level of 0.02mg of residue. ‘Stephen Mbithi, the chief executive at the Fresh Produce Exporters Association of Kenya warned that farmers could see their produce blocked from the EU market if they failed to comply with the regulations.’</p><p>Dr Mbithi observed that ‘Most small-scale growers’ – who cannot afford alternatives to what he described as of the most effective insecticides – ‘have so far not complied’. Smallholder farmers account for some 60% of total vegetable export production in Kenya. The Fresh Produce Exporters Association is urging farmers ‘to steer clear of the pesticide [dimethioate] until further notice’.</p><p>Kenyan producers’ associations are reportedly giving moral support to UK growers’ efforts to have the maximum permitted residue level raised tenfold. This however would leave the problem of zero tolerance from supermarkets unaffected. Kenyan horticulture industry leaders were philosophical: ‘we do not consider that organophosphates have much future in managing pests and diseases, and even though the alternatives are more expensive, they are more sustainable from a regulatory food safety point of view’, said Dr Mbithi.</p><p>In March 2011, discussions in the WTO SPS Measures Committee on private voluntary standards (PVS) saw concerns raised about the frequent absence of a scientific basis for some PVS measures and their deviation from international and official government standards. Concerns were also expressed about: the lack of harmonisation of PVS; the costs of compliance with PVS, particularly the disproportionate burden placed on small and medium-sized producers; and a lack of transparency in PVS. This led to calls for further work to explore the scope for elaborating guidelines of codes of conduct for the elaboration and application of PVS. However there was no consensus amongst WTO members on this point.</p>
		
		
