				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>With the pesticide review completed, the EU is now focusing on the more rigorous application of the new rules and regulations, which will come fully into effect from June 2011. This needs to be seen against the background of intensifying pressure from farmers’ organisations to strengthen the enforcement of EU SPS and food-safety controls in order to ensure a level playing field for competition between EU and third-country food suppliers. This has very real implications for ACP governments, both in terms of establishing effective food-safety and SPS compliance mechanisms and in terms of communicating standards and requirements to producers.</p><p>This is proving difficult even in advanced developing country exporters such as Thailand. It therefore gives rise to a substantial ‘aid for trade’ agenda, as regards food-safety control systems, the organisation of producer organisations and the establishment of effective dialogue mechanisms between government and private-sector bodies. These ‘aid for trade’ needs can only be partially met by COLEACP’s PIP initiative, given the limited budget available and the scale of the challenges faced.</p><p>A particular priority needs to be accorded helping smallholder farmers adjust to the new regulations, by facilitating access to cheaper alternative products or promoting new forms of pest management arrangements. If targeted support is not forthcoming across a range of ACP countries, smallholder farmers could be driven out of export-oriented supply chains.</p><p>The stricter residue standards applied by supermarkets also raise important questions as regards the need for a code of conduct or guidelines on the formulation and application of private standards.</p>
		</div>
		
